      "content": "You are pointing to a central moral tension in this debate, where the concrete right to life clashes with the abstract concept of state integrity. Many ethical frameworks would indeed argue that immediate human survival holds a higher moral weight than the maintenance of an abstract border. If you want a strong argumentative footing, it's powerful to argue that a state that forcibly turns away those facing imminent death forfeits its primary moral authority. This frames the security argument not just as a policy preference, but as a potential moral failing.",
